Virtual Private Gateway (VGW) in AWS is the AWS-side endpoint of a Site-to-Site VPN connection. It acts as the entry point into your VPC, allowing secure communication between your on-premises network and AWS resources.

🔑 Core Concepts
AWS-managed component → You don’t configure hardware; AWS handles it.

Attached to a VPC → Each VGW connects to one VPC at a time.

Works with Customer Gateway (CGW) → Together, they form the VPN connection.

Supports IPsec encryption → Ensures secure data transfer over the internet.

Routing options → Static or dynamic (via BGP).

⚙️ How It Works (Step-by-Step)
Create a Virtual Private Gateway in AWS.

Attach it to your VPC → This makes the VPC reachable via VPN.

Create a Customer Gateway → Represents your on-premises router/firewall.

Establish VPN Connection → AWS links the VGW and CGW using IPsec tunnels.

Update Route Tables → Add routes pointing to the VGW for on-premises networks.

Traffic Flow → Encrypted traffic passes through VGW into your VPC.

🚫 Limitations
Can attach to only one VPC.

No transitive routing (VPC A can’t talk to VPC B through VGW).

Less scalable for multi-VPC architectures.

✅ Bottom Line: The Virtual Private Gateway is your secure AWS endpoint for VPN connections — ideal for connecting a single VPC to your on-premises network. For larger, multi-VPC setups, Transit Gateway is the next step up.